Generational clashes: Jazz vs Rock vs Hip-Hop

Stefano Longo - UNI: sl4444

As time goes on, each generation condemens the next generation’s taste in music. Frequent critiques not only revolve around the musical component of new genres but they also target the kind of values associated with them. For example, as Rock rose to popularity in the 50’s, older generations that grew up listening to Jazz, or even Opera, found the new style disgraceful. Few decades later, in the 90’s and early 00’s, the same people that grew up with Rock started describing Hip-Hop in a similar way.

The generation clash is well-known but are the differences across genres as pronounced as they seem? The main point of this report is to try understand if Rock was as far from Jazz as Hip-Hop was from Rock.

Starting from the basics: vocabulary range

Under a musical point of view, newer genres are usually considered “inferior” and less sophisticated. Lyrics, however, while they do not seem to point to an opposite conclusion, do not completely confirm this. In fact, rock artists seem to be the ones using the widest vocabulary, followed by jazz artists and then hip-hop ones. However, this trend might at least partially be driven by the higher amount of rock songs in this database.

Genre Number of songs Number of new words per song
Jazz 4122 0.28
Rock 64845 0.59
Hip-Hop 8905 0.15

Quality rather than quantity: which 75 words are most frequent in each genre?

The word clouds below use size as a visual representation of frequency. They can intuitively express which words are most used and therefore suggest each genre’s focus. Love truly seems to make the world go round as this word is among most frequent ones across all three genres. More interestingly, however, the preponderance of words like baby and other female epithets in Rock and Hip-Hop songs potentially highlights how these two genres are man dominated. Lastly, the use of coarse words in Hip-Hop is reflect expectations and it is also the reason why I decided to not include as stop words even if the code example suggests otherwise.

Cosine similarity as a measure of statistical association

Cosine similarity measures the angular separation of two data vectors measured from zero and it therefore can be used to evaluate the similarity between two vectors. In this case, it is used to compare Jazz and Rock; Rock and Hip-Hop and finally Jazz and Hip-Hop.

Jazz and Rock emerge to be closer to one another than Rock to Hip-Hop. This might somehow justfy Rock fans to feel deprecate Hip-Hop even if they were similarly criticised in the 1960’s. Lastly, Jazz and Hip-Hop are the furthest apart.

Jazz Rock Hip.Hop
Jazz 1.00
Rock 0.89 1
Hip-Hop 0.58 0.69 1

Sentiment Analysis

Lastly, let’s verify whether the three genres focus on different emetions. Firstly, I categorise words dichotomously into either “positive” or “negative”, thanks to the sentimentr package. Assigning a 1 to positive words and a 0 to negative ones, allows me to take and average and estimate where on the spectrum each genre falls. It seems that newer genres have a more negative message than older ones.

Genre Sentiment Mean
jazz 0.58
rock 0.37
hiphop 0.29

Secondly, I conduct a more detailed analysis, categorizing words into 8 different emotions. By calculating how many words of each genre fall into a specific sentiment as a percentage over all the words in that specific genre, it is possible to evaluate whether some sentiments have become prevalent over time. This analysis highly reflect the previous one. Negative emotions like anger, disgust, fear, and sadness have all upward trends. In contrast, positive ones like anticipation, joy, surprise and trust show downward trends. It might be helpful to notice that the ratios add to 1 across genres, and not across emotions.

Summary

In conclusion, the generational clashes in the music word seem mostly supported by the data. The few similarities between the genres of Jazz, Rock and Hip-Hop are limited to the fact that they all tend to use relatively similar amounts of words, and focus somewhat extensively on love themes. However, all other indices used in this report point more towards differences than resemblence. Cosine similarity shows a rather low statistical association between the genres and the seniment analysis demonstrates how newer genres have incresing amounts of words with negative associations.
